    pearls: ["SnNOut and SpPIn: A Sensitive test with a Negative result rules OUT disease; a Specific test with a Positive result rules IN disease — this is the most tested concept in evidence-based assessment","Pretest probability MATTERS: ordering a D-dimer in a high-probability PE patient is inappropriate (false negatives are dangerous); ordering a CT-PA in a low-probability patient without D-dimer first is wasteful","Clinical decision rules (Ottawa, Wells, HEART) are evidence-based tools that standardize assessment and reduce diagnostic error — they should be applied consistently, not overridden by gut feeling","Likelihood ratios are more useful than sensitivity/specificity alone because they account for pretest probability: LR+ >10 is a strong positive shift, LR- <0.1 is a strong negative shift","The most common source of diagnostic error is cognitive bias, not lack of knowledge — implement 'diagnostic time-outs' to deliberately consider alternative diagnoses and challenge initial impressions"],
